TY  - JOUR
T1  - Interactive Effects of Procedural Justice and Outcome Negativity on Victims and Survivors of Job Loss
AU  - Brockner, Joel
AU  - Konovsky, Mary
AU  - Cooper-Schneider, Rochelle
AU  - Folger, Robert
AU  - Martin, Christopher
AU  - Bies, Robert J.
Y1  - 1994/04/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256835
DO  - 10.5465/256835
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 397
EP  - 409
VL  - 37
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Three studies respectively explored the interactive effects of procedural justice and outcome negativity on the victims of job layoffs, on survivors, and on lame ducks, employees who knew they would soon be laid off. Consistent results emerged for all three types. When procedural justice was perceived to be low, individuals reacted more adversely to the extent that outcomes were perceived to be negative. When individuals felt that procedural justice was relatively high, however, perceived outcome negativity was not related to their reactions.
AB  - Three studies respectively explored the interactive effects of procedural justice and outcome negativity on the victims of job layoffs, on survivors, and on lame ducks, employees who knew they would soon be laid off. Consistent results emerged for all three types. When procedural justice was perceived to be low, individuals reacted more adversely to the extent that outcomes were perceived to be negative. When individuals felt that procedural justice was relatively high, however, perceived outcome negativity was not related to their reactions.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256835
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256835
